<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-18T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="643" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d643">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1885</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-18T15:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 18, 1915, 3 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 19, 4.20 p.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2456. Can learn nothing definite as to Germany’s answer to note.
                                Probably nothing yet decided. Army and navy against any concession.
                                Only solutions talked of are either plan for certified passenger
                                ships already outlined to you, or mediation by our President of
                                question of submarine warfare and blockade of Germany. Situation
                                complicated by personal feuds between <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von Tirpitz</persName>, <persName>Von Müller</persName>,
                                    <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName>, Chancellor
                                and <persName corresp="#p_FEGASV1">Falkenhayn</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von Tirpitz</persName> being against
                                Chancellor and <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName>;
                                    <persName corresp="#p_FEGASV1">Falkenhayn</persName> inclined to
                                approve; <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von Tirpitz</persName>
                                neutral.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>